onduct a series of case studies in six key areas of economics. From the idea of the "multiple self" and notions of uncertainty and information, through market anomalies and competing concepts of value, to analytical distinctions based on gender and academic standing, economics is revealed as defying the modernist frame of a singular science. The authors conclude by showing how economic theory would change if the postmodern elements were allowed to flourish. A work of daring analysis sure to be vigorously debated, Postmodern Moments in Modern Economics is both accessible and relevant to all readers concerned about the modernist straightjacket that has been imposed on the way economics is thought about and practiced in the world today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aEconomicsxHistoryy20th century. 0aEconomics; History, 20th century. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh1 aAmariglio, Jack, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRuccio, David F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400880119423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400880119.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles